Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel offices in the then ČSSR: Čedok, sportsman, CKM, recrea and car tourism.
The travel offices sold mainly travels to the socialist eastern bloc countries, only selected in the West at that time.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (sotschý on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia entered a protesting course and therefore the travels to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries of the Eastern bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks).
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel to Poland individually or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Since then the travel offices also offered trips to the west, however, you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel office, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel office.
Even so, the thing hasn't been going on for a long time.
The so-called currency usage - the condition for a trip to the West - was only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without currency use it would have been impossible to drive the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holiday in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekly homes and dolls - a habit that continues to this day.
The current revolution of 1989 followed a re-evolution of the Czechs on foot.
While by 1989 a holiday in the DDR or Bulgaria was the size of everything, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A powerful paradox that you are not aware of today is the fact that you could not travel to the Czech most popular holiday country - Croatia until 1989 because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Since the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation has been lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, leading to a strong wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their trip to the West for a long time, each wanted to be there for at least a few days.
Thus, the Czech vacationers slept in the tent in Paris in the park, for who had already had the money for a stay in the hotel or in a pension.
A typical feature of foreign journeys from Czechs was then one with canned, beer and permanent sausage, etc. packed suitcases.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech Krone - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency free.
Our standard of living, as well as the averages, have increased in 1997 at another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel offices began to prepare regular flights after 1997 through charter flights, thereby allowing flights to deal with multiple discounts, which were incredibly approved in the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had a foreign exchange-free movement with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post office" travel came in 2000, when the high demand for the first direct charter flight in an exotic country was made - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying each year in far-reaching sunny countries; this year they fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel annually in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch, which marked our "postrevolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, thus definitely entering our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 TZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the cost of the holiday place.
