UNAM asphalt prevents loopholes
Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM developed modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs coming out of the road surface were to be taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 hitholes if the rainy season in the Metropolitana del Valle de México (city of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warns that if the release and maintenance of the asphalt ceiling is adequate, the number of hitholes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Technical holes" on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible developed asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which shows greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of roadblocks and thus avoid the occurrence of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the hardest part of the oil - is a hydrogen compound, from which part has a high molecular weight - the asphalts - and the other part is a low - the so-called malthene. Together they give the road surface its characteristic digital behavior.
Zidal conduct of the asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180°C as a liquid, at 120°C it is very smooth and at almost 50°C, while at very low temperatures it is broken.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the streets is not the same, but one day it changes depending on weather conditions and temperature changes," said the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City would have a flexible road block consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three asphalts were.
Among the top layers is a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt-built and then solidified stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer was built in asphalt.
If the vehicles are moving forward and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the roadmap.
"If it were a modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," the chemical engineer said.
"On the layer of wear", he said, "will be a final layer, the so-called layer of wear consisting of small stones, i.e. sand, which was also built in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they have to produce friction.
Those who receive and distribute most of the forces of this road block also need a suitable thickness and the material from which it is composed must be maintained.
